This paper is primarily focused on visual recognition and attention mechanisms in deep convolutional networks, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of stronger supervisory signals and human-derived attention maps, which could also be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also mentions human psychophysics and the interpretability of visual features, which could be relevant to the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Finally, the use of attention mechanisms in neural networks could also be relevant to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
